<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111233129/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/" class="size11">Unknown User</a>

<!---->

				
<span class="size11 darkgray">Dec 24, 2004</span>
                
                

            </div>
			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">I don't have this problem. If I caught a co-worker or friend doing something illegal, I would notify authorities immediately and assist any way I could in getting them convicted. Sounds harsh, doesn't it? Let me offer a counter-story.



I had a close friend in high school - He was a bright, technically-minded kid, he had most of a clue and was a fast thinker. His parents had divorced and left him in the care of his grandmother, who hated him with a passion. She would continually fault everything he did, even to the point of falsifying evidence against him just to punish him in front of family members. She viewed him as the reason her daughter and her husband broke up and punished him at any opportunity. She especially hated his passion for computing and would routinely break equipment and destroy manuals to set him back in his work. He persevered, often coming over to my house with a portable computer to try this or that. I knew when he started smoking marijuana, but he was my friend, so I didn't say anything. His grandmother's abuse intensified, his grades started slipping, he turned to drugs to dull the pain. I started seeing him less and less, but he was my friend, so I didn't say anything tp anyone. I took my first job as a network admin and saw even less of him. Finally, one day, he stopped coming over entirely. I assumed he was too busy, working his way out of his grandmother's house. I didn't pay attention or get worried, because he was my friend.



Two months after I last saw him, I learned that he had been involved in a drug deal that went badly. He had been shot 4 times, the back and through his legs. They dumped him in a ditch in the country. The police estimated it took him around 4 hours to bleed to death.  His fingers were all broken because he had been crawling along in the ditch, probably screaming for help. I didn't act because he was my friend, and how his blood is on my hands just the same as if I had pulled the trigger myself. If I had gotten the police involved earlier, when there was time for rehabilitation, the story would have ended differently.



If this situation comes up, and you're the one with the decision to make, just ask yourself, "Do I want the blood on my hands as well?" I'm sure you'll make the right decision.



(Sorry to long-post in someone else's blog, I just thought it was relevant to the question. Delete the comment if it offends.)

</span>
		</div>
           
    <div class="spacer"></div>

