            <a name="678986"></a>
            
	<div valign="top" class="content-listimage">

            
            <div class="size11 darkgray content-meta">
                <div class="floatleft" style="margin-top:-2px; margin-right:10px"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111233129/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/"><div class="userimage-defaulttiny"></div></a>
</div>


<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111233129/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/" class="size11">Unknown User</a>

<!---->

				
<span class="size11 darkgray">Dec 30, 2004</span>
                
                

            </div>
			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">My story did not fair so well...I was asked to find an application to monitor our firewall traffic.  I started to use Cyfin Reports for the 'manager ready' reports and they did provide some useful data.  But to really dig in I would use RnR ReportGen which allowed me to monitor ports, protocols etc...

Our programmer was using 95-98% of our T1 line daily!  I started to 'follow' him around the web and learned that he was studying up on various ways to avoid detection, IP spoofing etc.  He is an avid gamer...and I found that he had opened a series of TCP/IP ports allowing his gamer pals to access his server!!

Well...when this info was shared with my boss I was floored when all he got was a ceremonial slap on the wrist!  I was told to lock him out of the firewall, and keep tabs on him...before I left for a better opportunity - he back to his old tricks...I think he was running an Apache server (found he was reading up on Linux, and more articles about circumventing firewalls)

Anyway...sometimes the good guys aren't always rewarded for exposing frauds!  I'd love to be a fly on the wall when 'it' finally all falls down...</span>
		</div>
           
    <div class="spacer"></div>

    <div class="rule-gray"></div>
    <div class="spacer-small"></div>

    
            <a name="679079"></a>
            
	<div valign="top" class="content-listimage">

            
            <div class="size11 darkgray content-meta">
                <div class="floatleft" style="margin-top:-2px; margin-right:10px"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111233129/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/"><div class="userimage-defaulttiny"></div></a>
</div>


<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111233129/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/" class="size11">Unknown User</a>

<!---->

				
<span class="size11 darkgray">Jan 6, 2005</span>
                
                

            </div>
			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">In many cases there is no right or wrong.  Here, a rule was broken, but hey - none of us speed on the freeway, right?



I'm curious what the IP was, and what she intended to do with it.  The reason I'm curious is that so far, there isn't enough to show a crime.  And in fact, in some legal systems, she could have been within her rights.  For example, under those countries that grant authorship rights, if she had taken her *own* graphics home, and used them for her portfolio, then the company may have been operating outside the law to deny her those rights.  This occurs sometimes with Hollywood films (for example, I have a director's special of Koyannisqatsi, legally cut but without the "owner"'s permission!)



IANAL .. and it different countries make it real tricky to generalise.  But here's another story:  back in the 80s I was sent into a customer installation to repair some bugs in a customer's copy of Informix (an old DB), one which I had previously compiled and installed for them years before.  The supplier sent me the wrong source code tape and indeed it transpired that the supplier had lost their copy of the source for Informix.  (They went broke soon afterwards...)



Well, anyway, I was stuck in a different state, no source, no job to do, and no way to bill.  The IT manager took me out the back fire escape (the illegal smoking room) and quietly suggested to me that the last time I'd been on site, one of the employees had surreptitiously lifted a copy of the source code ....



And we were back in business!  Or were we?  Should I have refused to work on the stolen code?



iang



PS: Suzuran, just a personal opinion.  There is no blood on your hands.  You had no power to change the situation for the better.  Any choice you had taken might have ended up right, or just as likely would have made the situation worse.  Life sucks, and when our brains tell us to do nothing, it's because our brains know there is no way to be sure we are doing the right thing.</span>
		</div>
           
    <div class="spacer"></div>

    <div class="rule-gray"></div>
    <div class="spacer-small"></div>

    
            <a name="678992"></a>
            
	<div valign="top" class="content-listimage">

            
            <div class="size11 darkgray content-meta">
                <div class="floatleft" style="margin-top:-2px; margin-right:10px"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111233129/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/"><div class="userimage-defaulttiny"></div></a>
</div>


<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111233129/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/" class="size11">Unknown User</a>

<!---->

				
<span class="size11 darkgray">Jan 7, 2005</span>
                
                

            </div>
			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">I had a subordinate once, a programmer whom I had to fire for hacking. I was working with him at his computer, and we needed to do something with root privileges. So I leaned over his shoulder and typed the sudo command, with the root password (which he wasn't supposed to know). Well, it gave a strange error, like it wasn't able to access some file. Turns out he had aliased sudo and was capturing the root password! He claimed he was "just experimenting" but never really had a good explanation. So we fired him. I felt bad about it; I'd worked with him for a couple of years and he'd always done a good job, but you just can't allow that kind of stuff at the office,</span>
		</div>
           
    <div class="spacer"></div>

    <div class="rule-gray"></div>
    <div class="spacer-small"></div>

    
            <a name="1647250"></a>
            
	<div valign="top" class="content-listimage">

            
            <div class="size11 darkgray content-meta">
                <div class="floatleft" style="margin-top:-2px; margin-right:10px"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111233129/http://it.toolbox.com/people/ryvan/"><div class="userimage-defaulttiny"></div></a>
</div>


<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111233129/http://it.toolbox.com/people/ryvan/" class="size11">Angus Beath</a>

<!---->

				
<span class="size11 darkgray">Oct 9, 2007</span>
                
                

            </div>
			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">I think in a case like this, that it's usually quite clear what an employees rights and responsibilities are regarding the work place. The Chief noted that there is a clear information regarding the copying of internal documents. Nelson did the right thing - his responsibility is to the company in this instance. She knew what she was doing and also, I'd guess the outcome. It is <strong>her </strong>responsibility to work within the appropriate guidelines as provided by the employer. At the end of the day, if she hadn't behaved that way, there would have been no problem. I wonder - would she have absolved Nelson or blamed him for what happened had he seen her after her termination?<br><br>Had I been in Nelson's place I would have done the same thing as he did. It's my responsibility to my employer to help cover their backside in an instance like this. If you do nothing you become an accomplice. All that evil needs to win is for good people to do nothing (not that the female in this instance is necessarily evil - it's just a cool quote :) ).


</span>
		</div>
           
    <div class="spacer"></div>


